/strong></p> <p><a href=\"http://alaskamaritime.fws.gov/visitors-educators/wildlifeviewing/sitka.htm\">St. Lazaria Island</a>, located just fifteen miles southwest of Sitka, boasts some of the best bird-watching in all of Alaska. The city of Sitka and its surrounding conifer forests are also perfect for bird watching.</p> <p><strong>When to go:</strong></p> <p>The lush and temperate climate in Sitka and the surrounding area means that the bird-watching season in the southeast is a bit longer than in most parts of Alaska. In fact, birds of interest can be spotted on and near St. Lazaria Island all year long. For sightings during breeding or peak migration, however, plan a trip between April and September.</p> <p><strong>What you can expect to see:</strong></p> <ul> <li>Albatross: One of the largest flying birds in the world, the albatross is a bird every birder wishes to spot at one point or another. </li> </ul>\n<p class=\"photos\">\n<img src=\'http://rc-images.s3.amazonaws.com/7f6a3dc1-3465-493f-80e6-ab1f4a9be23d/media/253208/medium/253208.PNG?gen=1\' /><br />\n</p><ul> <li>Rhinoceros Auklet: With a horn resembling that of a rhinoceros, this adorable seabird is especially interesting to watch when it is young.</li> <li>Willow Ptarmigan: Easily recognizable by its marbled brown color and thick bill, Alaska&rsquo;s state bird can be seen all year round.</li> <li>Other seabirds: such as the ancient murrelet, shearwater, and storm-petrol are also commonly spotted feeding and migrating near Sitka.</li> </ul> <p>For a luxury vacation in one of Alaska&rsquo;s best birding regions, book a vacation at <a href=\"http://www.luxuryalaskanfishinglodge.com/188933/2011/07/28/how-to-plan-a-week-at-an-alaska-fishing-resort.html\">Talon Lodge</a> in Sitka. Call (888) 763-5630 to find out how to combine your birding endeavors with a first-rate fishing trip, five-star cuisine, and luxurious spa services.</p>\n<p class=\"tags\">More from Talon Lodge Blog: <a href=\'http://www.luxuryala